<paragraph blockId="10.[138,1185,586,675]" pageId="10" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis box="[138,280,586,610]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="273">Relationship.</emphasis>
This species closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okada" authorityYear="1968" box="[656,832,586,610]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata" subGenus="Amiota">
<emphasis box="[656,684,586,610]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="273">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[704,731,586,610]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="273">A.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[752,832,586,610]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="273">sinuata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the general morphology of male terminalia, but can be distinguished from it by the vertical lobe of gonopod being elongated basally (not elongated basally in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okada" authorityYear="1968" box="[643,723,651,675]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata">
<emphasis box="[643,723,651,675]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="273">sinuata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[138,807,715,739]" box="[138,807,715,739]" pageId="10" pageNumber="273">
